# Auth - Edge vs Node split

NextAuth v5's middleware runs in the **Edge runtime**, which forbids Node-only modules (`pg`, `bcryptjs`, `node:fs`, `node:crypto`). The config is split in two:

| File | Runtime | Contains |
|------|---------|----------|
| `src/lib/auth.config.ts` | Edge-safe | `trustHost`, `session`, `pages`, callbacks, **no providers** |
| `src/lib/auth.ts` | Node | spreads `authConfig` and adds the `Credentials` provider with `pg` + `bcryptjs` |
| `src/middleware.ts` | Edge | imports **only** `authConfig` and calls `NextAuth(authConfig).auth` |

**Next.js 16:** `npm run build` may warn that the **`middleware` file convention is deprecated** in favor of **`proxy`**. Routing still works; migrate using the official [middleware → proxy](https://nextjs.org/docs/messages/middleware-to-proxy) guide when ready.

## Rules

- Anything that touches `pg`, `bcryptjs`, or other Node APIs must live in `auth.ts`, never `auth.config.ts`.
- `trustHost: true` is required so NextAuth accepts `localhost` and arbitrary hosts in dev / on-prem.
- API route handlers (`src/app/api/**`) and server components import from `@/lib/auth` (the Node version) to call `auth()`.
- The JWT callback adds `id` and `role`; the session callback projects them onto `session.user`. See `src/types/next-auth.d.ts` for the type augmentation - update both if you add JWT fields.
